    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1948-09-07T00:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1948-09-07T00:00:00-05:00" n="253"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d253">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">800.014 Antarctic/9–748: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in New Zealand</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Scotten</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">secret</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Wellington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1948-09-07T17:00:00+12:00"
                            >September 7, 1948—5 p. m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>139. Re <gloss target="#t_Deptel1">deptel</gloss> 77, August 10.<note n="1"
                        xml:id="d253fn1">Not printed, but see footnote 1 to the Department of State
                            <hi rend="italic">aide-mémoire</hi> of August 9 to the Australian
                        Embassy, <ref target="#pg_996">p. 996</ref>.</note> Secretary External
                        Affairs<note n="2" xml:id="d253fn2">A. D. McIntosh.</note> states Prime
                        Minister<note n="3" xml:id="d253fn3">Peter Fraser.</note> is willing to “go
                    along” with American Antarctic proposals although closer <gloss target="#t_UN1"
                        >UN</gloss> relationship considered preferable. New Zealand Legation
                    Washington receiving instructions.<note n="4" xml:id="d253fn4">Despatch 297,
                        September 8, from Wellington, not printed, confirmed the contents of this
                        telegram and enclosed a memorandum of a conversation with officials of the
                        New Zealand Ministry of External Affairs indicating that although the New
                        Zealand Government’s first reaction to the American proposal had been
                        adverse, its final favorable decision was influenced by the United Kingdom
                        (800.014 Antarctic/9–848).</note>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Scotten</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
